  <BR><img src=http://www.mindspring.com/~suretang/images/usf2.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RPP/Raid Point information.</span><hr size=1> RPP works for raid oriented guilds, as was said before.<br>
<br>
Usually, RPP works when people feel like &quot; i have paid my dues and havent gotten crap to show for it !!!&quot;.<br>
<br>
IE, they are tired of seeing others win stuff  who dont raid as much as they do.<br>
<br>
Bonuses to RPP system.<br>
<br>
1. Everyone can purchase any item they have rpp for, within the constraints of the system.  No more &quot; this doesnt fit your class BEST &quot;.<br>
<br>
2. Encourage participation for members who might not want to go help on things where they dont have a chance at benifit ( ie epic raids where the job is to kill the mob and there is no loot ).<br>
<br>
3. Let members have clearly defined expectations of how fast they might or might not get loot.<br>
<br>
4. Make the guild in general stronger, as the members who raid the most ( ie put in the most effort ) WILL get the items.  Sorta like the republican &quot;trickle down&quot; theory.<br>
<br>
Negative aspects <br>
<br>
1. Focuses a guild on loot, and encourages members to focus on the loot aspect of the game.<br>
<br>
2. Acknowledges that there are members in your guild who might not participate in something if nothing is in it for them.. ie they wont go just to help a friend.<br>
<br>
3. Fosters resentment if you have members who for whatever reason cant play as much as they want to.. thus end up with negative RPP and no hope of ever getting anything on things they DO participate in.<br>
<br>
4. headache for SOMEONE to administer.<br>
<br>
5. Loot can go to someone's twink who raids alot, even if a &quot; main &quot; is there at the event and could use the item<br>
<br>
<br>
I personally find the idea of RPP distasteful, HOWEVER, i understand WHY the guilds that do it, do it.  It works for those guilds who are focused on raiding.  IMO, it will NOT work in guilds who profess a &quot; family &quot; atmosphere.<br>
<br>
One of the definitions of &quot; family &quot; guilds is one where members are not forced to attend any particular event, and have equal chances at items on the ones they DO attend.<br>
<br>
It is this reason family guilds normally fall behind raid guilds in equipping members, even when they have the level to do so ( no forced participation = less raiding, which = less gear for their members .. or gear aquired at a slower pace ).<br>
<br>
Also, Tani's explanation is also valid, in that assigning RPP to something a member could do with a group doesnt work.<br>
<br>
The only thing that bothers me about RPP in relation to the rest of the lanys community, is that many times people in RPP guilds will take advantage of those in NON rpp guilds to aquire loot without &quot; paying &quot; for it.<br>
<br>
You will see people in an RPP guild trying to solicit help for something like Phinny in kedge, where they could take it out with one group NP ( many non rpp guilds can as well ).  They will try to organize people from out of guild so they dont pay rpp for it.  I see this alot, and think of people trying to skirt their own system that is set up for them.  Sometimes they go on raids that are NON rpp to skirt their system too.. when they could just as easily set up a raid in their guild ( but then have to pay rpp ).<br>
<br>
They should just suck it up and pay the rpp, since that is the system they choose to play in.<br>
<br>
<br>
<br>
