<a href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=37645" target="_blank">"Only those who risk going too far can possibly know how far they can really go." - T.S. Eliot</a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#D5D4D5><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title><A HREF="http://www.ezboard.com/promotions/csc.html" TARGET="_blank" ><IMG SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/image/cscicon3.gif" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20" BORDER="0" align="absmiddle"></A> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/umystiquedekami.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MystiqueDeKami</A>&nbsp; <IMG HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10 SRC="http://www.ezboard.com/ezgfx/gicons/white_star.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I live here.... get out.</span><br> <font color=#000033>(1/7/02 5:16:02 am)</font><br>     <br>Community Supporter<br> <BR><img src=http://www.conquest-guild.com/members/yunna/Sigs/succicon.gif WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RPP/Raid Point information.</span><hr size=1> <!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Administration:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  The CQ RPP system was using a website frontend for a database.  It was quite easy to manage  necessitating only to enter the time / mob of a raid and to click checkboxes beside the members that were present (which was quite easy if done on a 2nd comp while raid was in progress).  It could also be made to be able to parse a snippet of eqlog.txt for people in the RPP members list that are present in the zone from a /who command.  It also allowed to sort by any column ascending or descending.  Listing by descending current RPP made it very easy to find which of those people that sent tells are in the top 5  of the highest person that wanted the item.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Twinks:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  In CQ a person could use RPPs towards any 55+ character they owned.  Characters under 55 could get RPP items ONLY if they were going to rot (lower priority than a negative player).<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Family guilds:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  As much as a family guild might say that people are not forced to attend raids, in most of them they are.  Family guilds are generally formed of a smaller number of people (because the more people you add the more they won't all feel like a family with everyone else) so key people aren't easily replaceable (like say your only epic cleric, or only necro that can use SC coffins, or your only planar wizard, etc etc).  If they miss raids thus forcing the others to either cancel a raid or make the raid much harder to execute (like the headache of SCing 20 people with large coffins) resentments WILL appear.  People will be either forced by peer pressure to attend or even if sentiments remain unspoken it will eventually create rifts between people.<br>
<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> Exploiting nonRPP people:</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->  There's two parts to this.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 1.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->About doing your own nonRPP raids to get RPP items:  Too easy to get items are not given RPP values.  For harder ones under CQ rules you WILL be charged the value of whatever you got even if it was completely with out of guild people.  If you try to make the raid in secret and it's found out it's highly frowned upon.  And in any sizable guild things like this are easily found out.  Exceptions to this can be made at the guild leader's discretion depending on the circumstances.  For example someone buying a RPP item with pp in ECom, having a RPP item MQed from a friend or a guild-friend (see explanation below what these are) getting say their epic with their base guild, or on a nonRPP raid because we don't have the time to get it for them in the near future.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE BOLD START--><b> 2.</b><!--EZCODE BOLD END-->About inviting nonRPP people to RPP raids:  Generally nonRPP members are not invited to raids, one of the goals and strengths of an uberguild being to be self sufficient.  However there are what we call &quot;guild-friends&quot;.  These people have an unlimited open invite to any and all raids and are members of the RPP system (they are technically members except for lack of guildchat, no access to things such as ST keys and ability to be part of a different guild while raiding with us).  On the rare ocassion that people who are not members of the RPP system are needed for a specific raid and an item they can use drops then a weighted roll between the RPP system and that person happens.  For example say we raided Dragon X and UberClericOnlyBP drops.  We had a total of 10 clerics attend, 8 that are members or guild-friends and 2 that we needed to invite from the outside.  Of the 8 RPP member clerics 5 need the items.  Both nonRPP clerics need the item.  A roll is made: 1-5 RPP ststem, 6 NonRPPCleric01, 7 NonRPPCleric02.  If one of the 2 outside clerics wins the item it's theirs.  If the RPP system wins the items it is distributed to the 5 RPP clerics that needed it according to RPP rules. <p><a href="http://eq.castersrealm.com/players/view_profile.asp?Id=18807" target="CRProfile" alt="Yunna's Profile" title="Yunna's Profile"><img src="http://www.conquest-guild.com/members/yunna/sig2001.jpg" border="0" alt=" "></a></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#E5E5E6><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub4.ezboard.com/ucakvalasc.showPublicProfile?language=EN>CakValaSC</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>I live here.... get out.</span><br> <font color=#000033>(1/7/02 8:24:53 am)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: RPP/Raid Point information.</span><hr size=1> what happens when a guild kills everything.. and theres nother knew to 